Speaker 1: The 100. The thing is the time release is that everybody's different, right? So when you do the study, they record, they—

Speaker 2: Keep doing the test over and over and over and over and record the reaction of people, and people—

Speaker 2: You know, your body changes, you know, over time. So your diet, you get some rest, you know, different—

Speaker 1: Factors basically.

Speaker 2: You're about to go out dinner. I would have you take your pill before you go to dinner, right? So—

Speaker 1: Now you're getting dressed, you do all of that, you take your pill now, you get activated and you feel—

Speaker 2: Like you're ready. Now you go eat or whatever, but the system is already fixed stuff I set up for—

Speaker 1: You because like any other medicine, when your stomach is full, the product gets swamped into—

Speaker 2: Other substances and it takes longer, you get diluted and all that kind of stuff, you see—

Speaker 1: What I'm saying? So take it at 6 o'clock in the evening before I go out to dinner, and if I come home at 12—

Speaker 2: At midnight, I don't have to take it again?

Speaker 1: Yes, you see, you did it already. Some people, they do half—

Speaker 2: And they take another half later, you see, I'm saying, like little technique you get to see for—

Speaker 1: Yourself what works better for you, you know what I mean?

Speaker 2: I understand you. So another question is, can you—

Speaker 1: Take it without alcohol, yes or no?

Speaker 2: Ideally no, but some people, they work with them, they can take—

Speaker 1: Alcohol or not, no problem. So it's mostly you to monitor how your body works because there is so—

Speaker 2: Many individuals and reactions are different, you know what I'm saying? So some people, they take with—

Speaker 1: Alcohol, no problem, but ideally any doctor, any medication, antibiotic meds, yeah, no alcohol, no—

Speaker 2: Caffeine, no, you know what I'm saying, stuff of that nature, you know.

Speaker 1: I get you, I get you.

Speaker 2: Yeah, perfect, thanks for this advice, Felice. Now I know what I'm doing. I was taking the wrong ones all along. I mean—

Speaker 1: You can take the other one too. The other ones are great. Don't lose them, keep them on a side, you're—

Speaker 2: Gonna need them. I think that's the one, I think that's the first one you gave me, and then I called—

Speaker 1: You back and say you gave me the wrong stuff, and then they sent me out the 100. But they're still—

Speaker 2: Good because we have people who still taking, who take the AC, they don't want to change to the AGV—

Speaker 1: Because AC works good for them. So don't underestimate those AC 340, the first pill you got—

Speaker 2: Don't underestimate it. But you say you sent them back?

Speaker 1: No, I told them I wanted the ones that were on—

Speaker 2: Facebook to work in 11 minutes.

Speaker 1: Yes. So they sent me out the hundreds around, just the other way—

Speaker 2: Around, I'm not sure.

Speaker 1: Yeah, the hundred is the good one. The hundred is the new one basically, but the—

Speaker 2: Other one is good as well. Don't underestimate them, that's what I'm saying. Keep them, those are—

Speaker 2: Difficulties, but there are patients who have no problem, they get activated quickly even with—

Speaker 1: Just a regular generic.

Speaker 2: I understand. Yeah, all right, so thanks for your advice. Have a good night.

Speaker 1: Thank you, bye-bye.
